const c1 = 'WHAT IS CLIMATE CHANGE?\n\nClimate change refers to long-term shifts in global temperatures and weather patterns. Since the 1800s, human activities have been the main driver - primarily burning fossil fuels.\n\nHOW IT WORKS:\nBurning fossil fuels releases greenhouse gases (CO2, methane) into the atmosphere. These gases trap heat from the sun - called the greenhouse effect.\n\nKEY FACTS:\n- Earth has warmed 1.2 degrees C since pre-industrial times\n- CO2 levels are at their highest in 800,000 years\n- Sea levels are rising 3.3mm per year\n- Extreme weather events are becoming more frequent\n\nGREENHOUSE GASES:\n- Carbon Dioxide (CO2): Fossil fuels, deforestation - 76% of emissions\n- Methane (CH4): Agriculture, landfills - 16% of emissions\n- Nitrous Oxide (N2O): Agriculture, fertilizers - 6% of emissions\n\nIMPACTS:\n1. Rising temperatures and more frequent heatwaves\n2. Changing rainfall - more floods and droughts\n3. Melting ice caps and rising sea levels\n4. Ocean acidification harming marine life\n5. Biodiversity loss and ecosystem disruption\n6. Food and water insecurity\n\nTHE PARIS AGREEMENT (2015):\nSigned by 196 countries, aims to limit warming to 1.5 degrees C. Countries submit emission reduction plans called NDCs.\n\nWHAT YOU CAN DO:\n- Reduce energy use at home\n- Choose plant-based foods more often\n- Use public transport, cycle, or walk\n- Support renewable energy\n- Spread awareness in your community';

const c2 = 'BIODIVERSITY AND ECOSYSTEMS\n\nBiodiversity refers to the variety of life on Earth - from genes to species to ecosystems.\n\nTHREE LEVELS:\n1. Genetic diversity - variation within species\n2. Species diversity - variety of different species\n3. Ecosystem diversity - variety of habitats\n\nWHY IT MATTERS:\n- 75% of food crops depend on animal pollination\n- 70% of cancer drugs come from natural sources\n- Forests absorb 2.6 billion tonnes of CO2 per year\n- Nature provides $125-145 trillion in services annually\n\nCURRENT CRISIS:\n- 1 million species face extinction\n- Species disappearing 100-1000x faster than natural rates\n- 75% of land surface significantly altered by humans\n\nFIVE MAIN THREATS:\n1. Land and sea use change (habitat destruction)\n2. Direct exploitation (hunting, fishing, logging)\n3. Climate change\n4. Pollution\n5. Invasive alien species\n\nCONSERVATION STRATEGIES:\n- Protected areas (17% of land, 10% of ocean)\n- Habitat restoration and rewilding\n- Sustainable agriculture and forestry\n- International agreements (CBD, CITES)\n- Community-based conservation';

const c3 = 'DEFORESTATION AND ITS IMPACT\n\nDeforestation is the large-scale removal of forests, primarily for agriculture, logging, and urban expansion.\n\nSCALE:\n- 10 million hectares of forest lost every year\n- That equals 27 football fields every minute\n- Since 1990, we have lost 420 million hectares\n- The Amazon has lost 17% of its forest in 50 years\n\nMAIN CAUSES:\n1. Agriculture (80% of deforestation) - cattle, soy, palm oil\n2. Logging (commercial and illegal)\n3. Infrastructure development\n4. Mining\n5. Urbanization\n\nIMPACTS ON CLIMATE:\n- Forests store 861 billion tonnes of carbon\n- Deforestation releases 10% of global CO2 emissions\n- Trees absorb CO2 through photosynthesis\n- Forests regulate local and regional rainfall\n\nIMPACTS ON BIODIVERSITY:\n- 80% of terrestrial species live in forests\n- Habitat fragmentation isolates populations\n- Keystone species loss causes ecosystem collapse\n\nIMPACTS ON PEOPLE:\n- 1.6 billion people depend on forests for livelihoods\n- Indigenous communities lose homes and culture\n- Increased flooding and landslides\n\nSOLUTIONS:\n- REDD+ (Reducing Emissions from Deforestation)\n- Sustainable Forest Management (FSC certification)\n- Reducing beef and palm oil consumption\n- Reforestation programs\n- Strengthening indigenous land rights';

const c4 = 'CARBON FOOTPRINT BASICS\n\nA carbon footprint is the total greenhouse gases produced by your actions, measured in CO2 equivalent (CO2e).\n\nAVERAGE FOOTPRINTS BY COUNTRY:\n- USA: 16 tonnes CO2e per person per year\n- UK: 8 tonnes\n- India: 2 tonnes\n- Global average: 4 tonnes\n- Target by 2050: Under 2 tonnes\n\nBIGGEST CONTRIBUTORS:\n1. Diet (especially beef and dairy) - up to 30%\n2. Transport (flights, cars) - up to 30%\n3. Home energy (heating, electricity) - up to 25%\n4. Shopping and consumption - up to 15%\n\nFOOD CARBON FOOTPRINT (kg CO2e per kg):\n- Beef: 60 kg\n- Lamb: 24 kg\n- Cheese: 21 kg\n- Pork: 7 kg\n- Chicken: 6 kg\n- Vegetables: under 2 kg\n\nTRANSPORT FOOTPRINT (g CO2e per km):\n- Short-haul flight: 255 g\n- Car (average): 171 g\n- Bus: 89 g\n- Train: 41 g\n- Cycling: 0 g\n\nHOW TO REDUCE:\n1. Eat less meat and dairy (biggest impact)\n2. Avoid flying when possible\n3. Use public transport or cycle\n4. Switch to renewable energy\n5. Buy less, buy second-hand\n6. Reduce food waste';

const c5 = 'OCEAN POLLUTION AND YOU\n\nOur oceans cover 71% of Earth and produce 50% of the oxygen we breathe. Yet they face unprecedented threats.\n\nSCALE OF POLLUTION:\n- 8 million tonnes of plastic enter oceans every year\n- That equals dumping a garbage truck of plastic every minute\n- 700+ marine species threatened by plastic\n- 90% of seabirds have plastic in their stomachs\n- 400+ ocean dead zones worldwide\n\nTYPES OF POLLUTION:\n1. Plastic pollution - bags, bottles, microplastics\n2. Chemical pollution - agricultural runoff, industrial discharge\n3. Oil spills\n4. Noise pollution - disrupts whale communication\n5. Thermal pollution - warm water from power plants\n\nIMPACTS:\n- Coral bleaching: 50% of reefs lost since 1950\n- Entanglement kills 100,000 marine mammals yearly\n- Microplastics found in human blood and lungs\n- Dead zones suffocate all marine life\n\nTHE GREAT PACIFIC GARBAGE PATCH:\n- Twice the size of Texas\n- Contains 80,000 tonnes of plastic\n- Mostly microplastics under 5mm\n\nWHAT YOU CAN DO:\n1. Refuse single-use plastics\n2. Carry reusable bag, bottle, and cup\n3. Participate in beach cleanups\n4. Choose sustainable seafood\n5. Support ocean conservation organizations';

const c6 = 'OCEAN ACIDIFICATION\n\nOcean acidification is called "the other CO2 problem." It is quietly transforming ocean chemistry with devastating consequences.\n\nHOW IT HAPPENS:\n1. We burn fossil fuels, releasing CO2\n2. About 30% of CO2 is absorbed by the ocean\n3. CO2 + water = carbonic acid\n4. More acid = lower pH\n\nTHE NUMBERS:\n- Pre-industrial ocean pH: 8.2\n- Current ocean pH: 8.1\n- This represents a 26% increase in acidity\n- By 2100, pH could reach 7.8 (150% more acidic)\n\nWHO IS AFFECTED:\n1. Coral reefs - dissolve in acidic water\n2. Shellfish - cannot form shells\n3. Fish - disrupted sense of smell and navigation\n4. Plankton - base of marine food web, produces 50% of oxygen\n\nECONOMIC IMPACTS:\n- Shellfish industry worth $1 billion in USA alone\n- Coral reefs support $375 billion in goods and services\n- 500 million people depend on reefs for food and income\n\nSOLUTIONS:\n- Reducing CO2 emissions is the only long-term fix\n- Local actions: reducing runoff, protecting seagrass\n- Marine Protected Areas to reduce other stressors';

const c7 = 'RENEWABLE ENERGY SOURCES\n\nRenewable energy comes from natural sources replenished faster than consumed. Unlike fossil fuels, they produce little to no greenhouse gas emissions.\n\nSOLAR ENERGY:\n- Costs dropped 90% in the last decade\n- Now the cheapest electricity source in history\n- A solar panel pays back its energy cost in 1-4 years\n- Lifespan: 25-30 years\n- Can be installed on rooftops, in deserts, on water\n\nWIND ENERGY:\n- Onshore wind is cheapest electricity in many countries\n- Offshore wind has stronger, more consistent winds\n- A single turbine can power 1,500 homes\n- Lifespan: 20-25 years\n\nHYDROPOWER:\n- Largest renewable source globally (16% of electricity)\n- Reliable and can be turned on/off as needed\n- Large dams can displace communities\n\nGEOTHERMAL:\n- Uses Earth internal heat\n- Available 24/7 regardless of weather\n- Iceland gets 66% of energy from geothermal\n\nENERGY STORAGE:\n- Main challenge for 24/7 renewable energy\n- Lithium-ion batteries most common\n- Green hydrogen is future potential\n\nGLOBAL PROGRESS:\n- Renewables supply 30% of global electricity\n- Target: 100% renewable electricity by 2050\n- Solar and wind now cheaper than coal in most countries';

const c8 = 'WASTE SEGREGATION BASICS\n\nProper waste segregation is the foundation of effective waste management. When sorted correctly, more can be recycled and less ends up in landfill.\n\nTHE FOUR MAIN CATEGORIES:\n\n1. RECYCLABLE (Blue/Yellow bin):\n- Paper and cardboard (clean and dry)\n- Glass bottles and jars\n- Metal cans and tins\n- Hard plastics\nNOT recyclable: greasy boxes, soft plastics, contaminated packaging\n\n2. COMPOSTABLE (Green/Brown bin):\n- Fruit and vegetable scraps\n- Coffee grounds and tea bags\n- Eggshells\n- Garden waste\nNOT compostable: meat, dairy (in home compost)\n\n3. GENERAL WASTE (Black bin):\n- Soft plastics\n- Contaminated packaging\n- Ceramics\n- Nappies and hygiene products\n\n4. HAZARDOUS (Special disposal):\n- Batteries (take to collection points)\n- Electronics (e-waste recycling)\n- Chemicals and paints\n- Medicines (return to pharmacy)\n\nTHE WASTE HIERARCHY:\n1. REFUSE - Do not create waste\n2. REDUCE - Use less\n3. REUSE - Use again\n4. RECYCLE - Process into new materials\n5. ROT - Compost organic waste\n6. DISPOSE - Landfill as last resort\n\nGLOBAL FACTS:\n- 2 billion tonnes of municipal waste generated annually\n- Only 13.5% is recycled\n- Landfills produce methane, a powerful greenhouse gas';

const c9 = 'SUSTAINABLE CITIES\n\nCities cover 3% of land but consume 75% of resources and produce 80% of greenhouse gas emissions. Making them sustainable is critical.\n\nKEY PILLARS:\n\n1. SUSTAINABLE TRANSPORT:\n- Public transport (metro, bus, tram)\n- Cycling infrastructure\n- Electric vehicles\n- Copenhagen: 62% cycle to work\n\n2. GREEN BUILDINGS:\n- Passive design (insulation, natural ventilation)\n- Solar panels and green roofs\n- Smart building management systems\n- Buildings account for 40% of energy use\n\n3. URBAN GREEN SPACES:\n- Parks and gardens\n- Green roofs and walls\n- Urban forests and street trees\n- Singapore: 47% green cover in a dense city\n\n4. WASTE MANAGEMENT:\n- Comprehensive recycling programs\n- Composting facilities\n- San Francisco: 80% diversion from landfill\n\n5. WATER MANAGEMENT:\n- Rainwater harvesting\n- Greywater recycling\n- Permeable surfaces to reduce flooding\n\nCASE STUDIES:\n- Copenhagen: Carbon neutral by 2025\n- Curitiba, Brazil: Pioneer of bus rapid transit\n- Freiburg, Germany: Solar city with car-free zones\n- Amsterdam: 800,000 bicycles for 800,000 people';

const c10 = 'WATER CONSERVATION\n\nOnly 3% of Earth water is fresh, and less than 1% is accessible for human use.\n\nWATER FACTS:\n- 2 billion people lack access to safe drinking water\n- Agriculture uses 70% of global freshwater\n- By 2025, half the world may face water scarcity\n- A dripping tap wastes 3,000 gallons per year\n\nWATER FOOTPRINT OF PRODUCTS:\n- 1 cup of coffee: 140 litres\n- 1 hamburger: 2,400 litres\n- 1 kg of beef: 15,000 litres\n- 1 cotton t-shirt: 2,700 litres\n- 1 kg of vegetables: 300 litres\n\nHOW TO CONSERVE AT HOME:\n1. Fix leaks immediately\n2. Take shorter showers\n3. Turn off tap while brushing teeth\n4. Run full loads in appliances\n5. Collect rainwater for garden\n6. Use drought-resistant plants\n7. Eat less meat (huge water footprint)\n\nCLIMATE AND WATER:\n- Changing rainfall patterns\n- More frequent droughts\n- Glaciers melting (water towers of the world)\n- More intense flooding';

const c11 = 'AIR QUALITY AND HEALTH\n\nAir pollution kills 7 million people per year - more than AIDS, malaria, and tuberculosis combined.\n\nMAIN POLLUTANTS:\n- PM2.5: Fine particles from combustion - most dangerous\n  Penetrates deep into lungs and bloodstream\n- NO2: From vehicles and power plants\n  Causes respiratory inflammation\n- Ozone: From sunlight reacting with pollutants\n  Damages lungs and vegetation\n- Carbon monoxide: From incomplete combustion\n  Reduces oxygen in blood\n- SO2: From coal burning\n  Causes acid rain\n\nHEALTH EFFECTS:\n- Respiratory: Asthma, COPD, lung cancer\n- Cardiovascular: Heart attacks, strokes\n- Neurological: Cognitive impairment in children\n- 99% of world population breathes air exceeding WHO guidelines\n\nMOST VULNERABLE:\n- Children (developing lungs)\n- Elderly\n- People with existing conditions\n- Low-income communities near pollution sources\n\nSOLUTIONS:\n- Transition to electric vehicles\n- Clean cooking fuels\n- Industrial emission controls\n- Urban green spaces (trees filter pollutants)\n- Active transport (cycling, walking)';

const c12 = 'FOOD SYSTEMS AND SUSTAINABILITY\n\nThe food system accounts for 26% of greenhouse gas emissions and uses 50% of habitable land.\n\nFOOD SYSTEM IMPACTS:\n- 70% of freshwater use\n- 80% of deforestation\n- 1/3 of all food produced is wasted\n\nCARBON FOOTPRINT (kg CO2e per kg of food):\n- Beef: 60 kg\n- Lamb: 24 kg\n- Cheese: 21 kg\n- Pork: 7 kg\n- Chicken: 6 kg\n- Rice: 4 kg\n- Vegetables: under 2 kg\n\nFOOD WASTE:\n- 1.3 billion tonnes wasted per year\n- 8% of global greenhouse gas emissions\n- Costs 1 trillion dollars per year\n\nREDUCING FOOD WASTE:\n1. Plan meals and make shopping lists\n2. Store food properly\n3. Understand date labels\n4. Use leftovers creatively\n5. Compost unavoidable waste\n\nSUSTAINABLE DIET:\n1. Eat more plants, less meat\n2. Choose local and seasonal produce\n3. Reduce processed and packaged foods\n4. Grow your own food\n5. Support sustainable farmers\n\nVegan diet uses 75% less land, 54% less water, 73% less emissions than average diet.';

const c13 = 'CLIMATE JUSTICE\n\nClimate justice recognizes that those who contributed least to climate change suffer the most.\n\nTHE INJUSTICE:\n- Richest 10% responsible for 50% of emissions\n- Poorest 50% responsible for only 10% of emissions\n- Yet the poorest are most vulnerable to climate impacts\n\nVULNERABLE GROUPS:\n1. Low-income countries - less resources to adapt\n2. Indigenous peoples - lose lands and livelihoods\n3. Women and girls - more vulnerable to climate disasters\n4. Future generations - inherit consequences of today\n5. Small island states - entire nations face submersion\n\nCASE STUDIES:\n- Bangladesh: 1m sea level rise displaces 17 million people\n- Sub-Saharan Africa: Crop yields could fall 50% by 2050\n- Pakistan: 2022 floods affected 33 million people\n- Pacific Islands: Maldives, Tuvalu face submersion\n\nCLIMATE JUSTICE DEMANDS:\n1. Ambitious emission cuts by wealthy nations\n2. Climate finance for developing nations\n3. Technology transfer\n4. Loss and damage compensation\n5. Inclusion of marginalized voices\n6. Just transition for fossil fuel workers\n\nINTERNATIONAL MECHANISMS:\n- Green Climate Fund: $100 billion per year pledge\n- Loss and Damage Fund (established COP27)\n- Adaptation Fund';

const c14 = 'MARINE ECOSYSTEMS\n\nMarine ecosystems cover 71% of our planet and contain 97% of all water.\n\nMAJOR MARINE ECOSYSTEMS:\n\n1. CORAL REEFS:\n- Cover less than 1% of ocean floor\n- Home to 25% of all marine species\n- Called "rainforests of the sea"\n- Provide food and income for 500 million people\n- Threatened by warming, acidification, and pollution\n\n2. MANGROVES:\n- Coastal forests that grow in saltwater\n- Nurseries for 75% of tropical fish species\n- Store 3-5x more carbon than tropical forests\n- Protect coastlines from storms and erosion\n\n3. SEAGRASS MEADOWS:\n- Nurseries for fish and invertebrates\n- Sequester carbon 35x faster than tropical forests\n- Filter water and stabilize sediments\n\n4. OPEN OCEAN:\n- Largest ecosystem on Earth\n- Home to whales, sharks, tuna, squid\n- Phytoplankton produce 50% of Earth oxygen\n\n5. DEEP SEA:\n- Below 200m depth\n- Least explored ecosystem\n- Home to bioluminescent creatures\n- Threatened by deep-sea mining\n\nFOOD WEBS:\nPhytoplankton -> Zooplankton -> Small fish -> Large fish -> Top predators\n\nKEYSTONE SPECIES:\n- Sea otters control sea urchin populations\n- Sharks regulate fish populations\n- Whales fertilize ocean with nutrient-rich waste';

const c15 = 'SUSTAINABLE FISHING\n\nFish provide 20% of animal protein for 3 billion people. But overfishing is pushing many species to collapse.\n\nTHE OVERFISHING CRISIS:\n- 90% of fish stocks are fully exploited or overfished\n- 33% of commercial fish stocks are overfished\n- Bluefin tuna populations have declined 97%\n- Atlantic cod collapsed in 1992 - still not recovered\n\nPROBLEMS WITH INDUSTRIAL FISHING:\n1. Bycatch - 40% of all catch is unintended species\n2. Bottom trawling - destroys coral and seafloor habitats\n3. Ghost fishing - lost gear continues catching fish\n4. Illegal fishing - worth $23 billion per year\n\nSUSTAINABLE METHODS:\n- Pole-and-line fishing (no bycatch)\n- Handline fishing\n- Trap and pot fishing\n- Responsible aquaculture\n\nMARINE PROTECTED AREAS:\n- Currently protect 8% of the ocean\n- Target: 30% by 2030\n- Allow fish populations to recover\n\nCONSUMER CHOICES:\n- Look for MSC (Marine Stewardship Council) certification\n- Choose lower in the food chain (sardines, mackerel)\n- Avoid endangered species (bluefin tuna, shark fin)\n- Reduce overall fish consumption';

const c16 = 'PLASTIC POLLUTION CRISIS\n\nPlastic was invented in 1907. Since then, 9.2 billion tonnes have been produced. Only 9% has been recycled.\n\nPLASTIC BY THE NUMBERS:\n- 400 million tonnes of plastic produced every year\n- 8 million tonnes enter the ocean annually\n- 5 trillion pieces of plastic in the ocean\n- Plastic takes 400-1000 years to decompose\n- Humans consume about 5g of microplastics per week\n\nTYPES OF PLASTIC POLLUTION:\n1. Macroplastics - bottles, bags, packaging, fishing gear\n2. Microplastics (under 5mm) - from degraded plastics, synthetic fibres\n3. Nanoplastics - can enter cells and cross blood-brain barrier\n\nHEALTH IMPACTS:\n- Endocrine disruption (BPA, phthalates)\n- Found in human blood, lungs, placentas, breast milk\n- Potential carcinogens\n\nTHE SOLUTION HIERARCHY:\n1. REFUSE - Do not accept single-use plastics\n2. REDUCE - Buy less packaged products\n3. REUSE - Use durable alternatives\n4. RECYCLE - Only as a last resort\n\nSINGLE-USE ALTERNATIVES:\n- Plastic bags -> Reusable cloth bags\n- Plastic bottles -> Stainless steel bottle\n- Plastic straws -> Metal or bamboo straws\n- Plastic wrap -> Beeswax wraps\n- Plastic cutlery -> Bamboo or metal cutlery';

const c17 = 'GREEN TECHNOLOGY AND INNOVATION\n\nGreen technology (cleantech) uses renewable materials and energy, reduces emissions, and has minimal environmental impact.\n\nKEY TECHNOLOGIES:\n\n1. ENERGY STORAGE:\n- Lithium-ion batteries (EVs, grid storage)\n- Solid-state batteries (next generation)\n- Green hydrogen (seasonal storage)\n\n2. ELECTRIC VEHICLES:\n- Zero tailpipe emissions\n- 3x more efficient than combustion engines\n- Battery costs dropped 97% since 1991\n- 10 million EVs sold in 2022\n\n3. CARBON CAPTURE (CCS):\n- Captures CO2 from industrial processes\n- Direct Air Capture removes CO2 from atmosphere\n- Currently expensive but costs falling\n\n4. GREEN HYDROGEN:\n- Produced by electrolysis using renewable energy\n- Zero emissions fuel for industry and transport\n- Key for decarbonizing steel, cement, shipping\n\n5. VERTICAL FARMING:\n- Grows food in stacked layers indoors\n- Uses 95% less water than conventional farming\n- No pesticides needed\n- Year-round production\n\n6. SMART BUILDINGS:\n- AI-optimized heating and cooling\n- Automated lighting\n- Can reduce building energy use by 30%\n\nEMERGING TECHNOLOGIES:\n- Lab-grown meat (90% less land, 80% less water)\n- Perovskite solar cells (cheaper, more efficient)\n- Nuclear fusion (potentially limitless clean energy)';

const c18 = 'CIRCULAR ECONOMY\n\nThe circular economy is an alternative to the linear "take-make-dispose" model. It keeps resources in use for as long as possible.\n\nLINEAR vs CIRCULAR:\nLinear: Extract -> Make -> Use -> Dispose\nCircular: Design -> Make -> Use -> Recover -> Regenerate\n\nTHREE PRINCIPLES:\n1. Design out waste and pollution\n2. Keep products and materials in use\n3. Regenerate natural systems\n\nCIRCULAR STRATEGIES:\n- Refuse: Avoid unnecessary products\n- Reduce: Use less material\n- Reuse: Use products multiple times\n- Repair: Fix broken products\n- Remanufacture: Rebuild to original quality\n- Recycle: Process into new materials\n\nBUSINESS MODELS:\n1. Product-as-a-Service - lease instead of sell\n2. Industrial Symbiosis - one company waste is another resource\n3. Sharing Economy - maximize utilization\n4. Repair and Remanufacturing\n\nECONOMIC OPPORTUNITY:\n- Could generate $4.5 trillion by 2030\n- Create 700,000 new jobs in Europe alone\n- Reduce CO2 emissions by 48% by 2030\n\nPOLICY EXAMPLES:\n- EU Circular Economy Action Plan\n- Right to Repair legislation\n- Extended Producer Responsibility';

const c19 = 'SOIL HEALTH AND AGRICULTURE\n\nHealthy soil is the foundation of all food production. A single teaspoon contains more microorganisms than there are people on Earth.\n\nSOIL FACTS:\n- Soil stores more carbon than all plants and the atmosphere combined\n- 95% of our food comes from soil\n- Takes 500-1000 years to form just 2.5cm of topsoil\n- We are losing 24 billion tonnes of fertile soil every year\n\nTHREATS TO SOIL:\n1. Chemical fertilizers and pesticides kill soil organisms\n2. Monoculture farming depletes nutrients\n3. Overgrazing compacts soil\n4. Erosion from deforestation\n5. Urbanization seals soil under concrete\n\nSUSTAINABLE PRACTICES:\n1. Composting - adds organic matter and nutrients\n2. Crop rotation - prevents nutrient depletion\n3. Cover cropping - protects soil between main crops\n4. Reduced tillage - preserves soil structure\n5. Agroforestry - integrates trees with crops\n6. Organic farming - avoids synthetic chemicals\n\nREGENERATIVE AGRICULTURE:\nGoes beyond sustainable to actively restore soil health and sequester carbon:\n- No-till or minimal tillage\n- Diverse crop rotations\n- Integrating livestock\n- Maintaining living roots year-round\n\nWHY IT MATTERS FOR CLIMATE:\nHealthy soils can sequester 1.85 billion tonnes of carbon per year.';

